{"key":"processedPost-13683840","value":{"id":13683840,"first":13683768,"last":18482889,"when":1293324364,"utime":"12/26/10 02:46 AM","content":"Oyster producers often use vertical straw logs to get more substrates crammed into less space.&nbsp; The drawback is that your moisture is pulled by gravity to the bottom of the log, saturating it and starving the top of the log for moisture.<br />Also, more than half the weight of the log is usually sitting on the floor.&nbsp; The cable from above is mostly to prevent the log from tipping over.&nbsp; You can do cubes this way, but you need to cut a small circle around each pin that forms.<br />That's why I prefer to sit them on tables or shelves, unwrapped.<br />RR<br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/10-31/123093301-P_ostreatus_straw_log-discarded.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/10-31/123093301-thumb_P_ostreatus_straw_log-discarded.jpg\"></a>","title":"Re: Hanging Straw Logs."}}